# AMS 101

## AMS Intro

### Definition of AMS

An Agency Management System (AMS) is a software solution designed to help insurance agencies streamline their operations, manage policies and clients, and improve overall efficiency.

### Importance of AMS in agency operations

* AMS plays a crucial role in automating and centralizing agency processes, reducing manual work, and enhancing productivity.  
* It provides a comprehensive view of client information, policies, and documents, enabling quick access and efficient management.

### Overview of how AMS benefits agencies

* Improved organization and accessibility of client data and policies.  
* Streamlined workflows and automated tasks, reducing manual errors.  
* Enhanced customer service through faster response times and personalized interactions.  
* Better tracking of commissions, renewals, and policy changes.  
* Advanced reporting and analytics for data-driven decision-making.

## What is an AMS?

### Role of AMS in streamlining agency processes

* AMS acts as a centralized hub for agency operations, consolidating data and providing tools for efficient policy management, client communication, and reporting.

### Key functionalities and capabilities of an AMS

* Client and policy database: Store and organize client details, policy information, and related documents.  
* Quoting and proposal generation: Generate quotes and proposals for clients, leveraging pre-defined templates and data.  
* Policy and document management: Manage policies, endorsements, certificates, and other relevant documents.  
* Commission tracking and management: Track and manage commissions earned from policies and monitor agent compensation.  
* Reporting and analytics: Generate reports on sales, performance, retention, and other key metrics to gain insights into agency operations.  
* Integration with third-party tools: Seamlessly integrate with accounting software, CRM systems, carrier portals, and other tools to enhance efficiency.

## How do agencies use an AMS?

### Agency workflow management

* Utilize AMS to automate and streamline agency workflows, reducing manual effort and improving efficiency.  
* Assign tasks, track progress, and set reminders for policy renewals, claims processing, and other important activities.

### Client and policy management

* Store and manage client information, including contact details, policy history, notes, and interactions.  
* Easily access policy details, coverage information, and endorsements for effective policy management.

### Document and data organization

* Digitally store and organize policy documents, endorsements, certificates, and other relevant files.  
* Enable quick and easy retrieval of documents when needed.

### Reporting and analytics

* Leverage the AMS's reporting capabilities to generate detailed reports on sales, revenue, retention, and other performance metrics.  
* Analyze data to identify trends, track agency growth, and make data-driven decisions.

### Communication and Collaboration

* Use the AMS to communicate with clients, carriers, and team members through integrated email, messaging, and document-sharing features.  
* Collaborate on policies, claims, and other tasks within the AMS platform, ensuring everyone has access to the latest information.

# Philosophy of Fuse

## AMS Systems & Automated Marketing 

In order to buy Fuse, you need an AMS to get the data into Fuse. It’s a non-negotiable. Majority of the AMS’ have a built in marketing automation product. It would be silly if they didn’t. 

The problem is, Fuse exists because the AMS can’t fully meet the needs of the agency. 

### Problems the Agency Face

After an agency buys their AMS, they very quickly find out the following problems that are not solved for: 

* The marketing automation features built into the AMS don't allow for enough flexibility. Agencies can't trigger messages or do the cross selling that they need to in order to be successful .  
* The agency is on their own.   
  * Management systems support a ton of functionality BUT typically will not provide the 1:1 experience that our team does.   
  * Management system tools are typically DIY vs. our philosophy.  
* The content is weak or nonexistent. This puts more work on the agency.  
* The email builder does not allow for flexibility and the emails don't look attractive.  
* The process of setting up and/or maintaining a campaign are clunky and labor intensive. They are not true set it and forget it systems and require constant monitoring and checking to launch and run campaigns.

## Why Do Agencies Buy Fuse? 

Our goal is to be everything but the AMS. 

Creating an AMS is not on the horizon because all the AMS systems out there do that job correctly and effectively. We don’t need to re-create that working system. But, we have an answer for the rest of the issues that agencies have (after buying their AMS system): 

* True Marketing Automation  
  * Fuse offers a wide range of tools and features to streamline marketing efforts, automate repetitive tasks, and enhance customer engagement. It’s flexible enough to fit all the needs of an insurance agency.   
* Time and Cost Savings  
  * By automating marketing tasks, Fuse can save significant time and effort. It allows users to create personalized email campaigns, build their book of business, and track customer interactions more efficiently.   
  * This can result in cost savings by reducing the need for manual labor or outsourcing marketing activities.  
* Enhanced Customer Communication  
  * Fuse enables insurance agencies to communicate more effectively with their clients because the content is written for the insurance agency’s clients.   
  * This helps agencies build stronger relationships with customers, increase client retention, and generate more referrals.  
* Lead Generation and Tracking  
  * The platform offers lead generation tools to capture and manage potential EXISTING customers. It allows agencies to track leads, monitor their engagement, and automate follow-up actions. This helps streamline the sales process and improve conversion rates.  
* Training and Support  
  * We offer training and support to help agencies maximize the benefits of Fuse.   
  * We provide resources, webinars, and a dedicated support team to assist users in implementing and utilizing the platform effectively.

## Why Does an Insurance Agency Need Fuse? 

A different way to think about it is “what would they be doing if they didn’t have it?” 

* Some agencies rely on their AMS. But as we covered, it’s tougher to rely on AMS capabilities for marketing automation.   
* Insurance agencies make their money during renewal.   
* Without proactively reaching out to clients to nurture that relationship, they are not guaranteed that renewal. Instead, it’s a major risk.   
  * If the only time you hear from your agency is during renewal, they are not doing you a service.   
* On the flip side, how does an insurance agent have time to personally reach out to all their clients?  
  * The average insurance agent has around 500 clients in their BOB. Managing those relationships would be a nightmare.   
* There are obviously other reasons to use Fuse, but on this small piece alone \- it’s a no brainer.

  * Insurance is only one of their verticals.

  * AZ is mostly a Pipeline management tool.   
  * It lacks on the marketing automation side because it’s not automated \- it’s one off.   
  * It also does not work with a lot of AMS

### To Sum It Up

* The automation that Fuse has paired with communicating with agency clients at the right time is the reason we win.   
* We really don’t have a competitor that does everything we do.   
* On the Forge side, there are more direct competitors compared to Fuse. 

## Fuse’s Shortcomings 

We’d be remiss and ignorant to not have a discussion around where we fall short. 

* This product is built on factors that are hard for our team to control: the client’s data & an external AMS system.   
  * If either of those items are malfunctioning, Fuse will not perform 100%.   
  * This isn’t necessarily a bad thing, but you run the risk of putting a lot of eggs in one basket. We are still responsible for the experience.   
* The system itself is intimidating.   
  * In order to help the most amount of agents, you need to create a robust system. The more complication that is added to systems, the tougher they are for our team to manage.   
  * Again, not a bad thing, but something to wrap your head around.   
* Insurance as a whole is going through a hard market.   
  * Personal lines are a tough sell.   
  * Commercial lines are doing okayish.   
  * We sell exclusively to insurance agents, our team needs to adapt to have people see the value in our product and keep them renewing their subscriptions. 

Part of being a successful company is understanding where we might fall short. Without understanding “here is where we might fail” we cannot consider “here is what we are amazing at.”

* You have to commit both to memory.

## Fuse Product Overview

When working with Fuse, it’s important to remember that Fuse is as functional as the data it is fed. We have to configure the settings in order to make it work for the client’s data. 

### Signing In

* Go to agencyrevolution.com and sign in using your credentials. 

### Searching for a Realm/Admin Dashboard

* If you sign in, you should be taken to your demo site. However, sometimes it leaves you where you left off last.   
* Select gear icon \> administration \> client dashboard   
* This brings you to the admin dashboard that allows you to search for any realm.   
* There are charts with different categories  
  * Management System   
  * Integration Status   
  * Sync Issues   
  * Implemented Percentage   
  * Event Detector Ignored   
* As you scroll down, your dashboard will display accounts that have an active realm and an active list. This prevents mistakes\!   
* Within these accounts, there are two categories: Our Clients & Sandbox Lists  
* Both sections have the same top navigation bar. There are a couple of key labels to know what they mean:   
  * **Realm name**: This is typically the domain name.   
  * **List enabled**: Indicates if the list is turned on.  
  * **Event detector**: Indicates that an important event has occurred on a customer record, which may be a reason to add them to, or remove them from a campaign. If this is turned off or on, we should know why.   
  * **List type**: One integration with one instance of a management system.  
  * **Integration Status**: Is an AMS connected?   
  * **Created At**: The date the realm was created.   
  * **Last Notification/Download/Warnings**:   
    * Notification: This is when the management system "tells" Fuse that there is new/updated data  
    * Download: This is when Fuse retrieves the new/updated data so it can be processed and synced into Fuse  
    * For an API-based integration like AMS360, these descriptors are perfectly fitting. AMS notifies Fuse every time any record is updated. Then Fuse connects to the AMS database and downloads the updated record so it can be processed.  
    * For non-API integrations like file uploads, Fuse considers it a "notification" when the files are received. However, there is then no need for a "download". Fuse doesn't need to reach out to the management system to fetch the new data. The new data was all included in the "notification" (the uploaded files) so for those integrations, the "download" part is irrelevant.  
    * Based on that understanding of "Notifications" and "Downloads", the warning levels mean:  
    * Warning \= No "notifications" have been received recently  
    * Urgent \= No "downloads" have occurred recently  
* In the top right, there is a search bar. Enter the client’s domain or sandbox name that you are looking for.   
  * Click on the domain name to get to the account. 

### What Should a Realm Look Like

* When you sign into a realm, you should be checking a couple of areas each time:   
  * Within the client dashboard, check when the last sync was.   
  * Make sure the email open rate is an appropriate metric.   
  * Check any alerts in the top right, select see all alerts   
  * Verify that there is nothing wrong with the mapping or syncing of their account.   
    * There are other alerts that appear when you’re creating campaigns. Those alerts are less important than mapping/syncing alerts.   
    * Handle any alerts you can handle or prepare communication to the client to take care of them.   
* One thing to keep in mind is what the user can see and they cannot see.   
  * You can be an Agent or a Manager within Fuse.   
  * **Agents** have a modified dashboard view which gives them access to:  
    * Dashboard  
    * Survey & Feedback  
    * Outbox  
    * Texting  
    * In addition to modified access for Agent users, the Dashboard, Survey & Feedback, and Outbox sections of Fuse are filtered so that Agents can **only see their data**. This maintains privacy amongst Agent users but, more importantly, presents an Agent’s specific items that need attention.

### Mapping/Syncing Errors  

Generally speaking, if there is a mapping or syncing error, the client will have to get involved to fix it. 

* Syncing/Mapping Alert  
  * If Fuse hasn't received or been able to download new data for a few days, it creates an "out of sync" alert.   
  * The 3 ways in which Fuse alerts the client when their list is out of sync:   
    * under the alarm bell in Fuse  
    * via daily SMS  
    * via weekly recap email  
  * However, some clients still don’t acknowledge the error, so our team should reach out to them.   
    * File review is the most important step\! Nothing is going to happen until the File Review is done   
    * Make sure everything is mapped before uploading new files  \- the client HAS to do the work with mapping   
* Can our team fix it?   
  * In most cases the team can't fix it on their own. There's a definite element of "it depends" here.  
  * It depends on the management system and what's wrong with it.  
  * We have some integrations where all the client needs to do is enter their management system login credentials from Fuse, and that connects the integration.   
  * So, for example, if a CX team member sees that a setup step like "Login to QQ Catalyst" is broken, they can't fix it themselves but they can definitely help by linking the client to that page and telling them they need to log back into QQ from there to fix the integration.  
  * Or, for file upload lists like Epic, TAM, and EZLynx, if the page shows that we haven't recently received one or more of the required files, they can help by getting the client to upload those files, or see if their management system is failing to run the scheduled reports, etc.  
  * That being said, fixing a broken integration can sometimes be really straightforward (like "hey, you need to upload your files\!" or "come log back into your management system from Fuse")  
  * But at times it can also be a lot more complex and nuanced, requiring a bit more knowledge of how to troubleshoot the issue and identify when there might be a bug or complication as opposed to something simpler.  
    * If it looks straightforward to fix (or help the client fix), go for it\!  
    * If you're not sure or the straightforward fix doesn't seem to be working, bring it to the Integration Team\!

  * Mapping changed during one point, moving data from one area to another.  
  * We improved our logic or programming to fix an issue, so the numbers may have shifted.

#### Agency & Locations 

This is handled during the implementation step, but our team has to determine how many locations exist for the realm. 

##### 

##### **One Location**

* Fill out the information present. 

##### **Multiple Locations (Not available for Xanafuel realms)**

* Increase the location limit.   
* In Fuse, click on the gear icon in the top right.  
* In the dropdown list, click Administration.  
* From the next dropdown, click Realm Management.  
* In the search bar, copy and paste/type in the URL of the realm you are working on.  
* Find and click on the Fuse realm that shows up in the search results that matches the URL.  
* Click on the General tab in the top left.  
* Click the dropdown box under Location Limit.  
* In the dropdown, find and select the number of locations you are adding total.  
* Click the number that matches the number of locations.  
* Click the blue Save button.  
* Return to the Fuse realm.   
* Add Additional Locations  
  * After adding the first/main office, add additional office locations by clicking on the Add a Location button in the top right.   
  * Add a location for each additional physical office location.  
* Mapping the Location  
* After adding an additional location, click the location dropdown and select the location you just added.  
* Next, scroll down to the end of the Agency Info section.  
* Here, you'll see a field titled Location Mapping.  
* Below this, click the text link" Configure this list" in the Configure New List section.  
* Check the Office Name option.  
* Click Finish.  
* Scroll down to Location Mapping at the bottom of the Agency Info section for the new location.  
* Click the dropdown option and select the office name that matches the location you are adding (this is pulling directly from the AMS so it is whatever the agency names it on their side, which could require consulting with the Project Manager).  
* Click Save to successfully add the new location. Repeat for each additional location. 

Notes About Locations

* Only superusers can change the location limit on a realm. Once we increase the limit, the client can add locations up to the number we've allowed.  
* If you use the preview feature of the campaign with multiple locations, the email preview will use the main agency settings. However, you can preview the email for the different locations in the “Save and Preview” page on each email editor.   
* All settings under the “Agency and Locations” section, as shown below are location specific.

##### 

##### **Timezone**

In order for Fuse campaigns and broadcasts to be sent out and scheduled accurately, you will need to set the time zone to match where their main office is located. This is to ensure that if a client sends out a message to clients through Fuse, it will send out based on their timezone.

##### 

##### **Email Theme & Colors** 

Customize your emails to reflect each agency or location. By default, your location will have the same theme as your main agency. You can change these details below and customize specific locations.

Set up the email theme: Typically, it makes sense to select a default theme with a white background if the client does not have a transparent logo. You can set up multiple themes for a realm but only one can be the default. Generally only one theme is used per realm.

Colors: You can customize the colors for this email or apply them to all uses of this theme.

##### **Social Media** 

Next, you’ll need to activate and add any applicable social media links to Fuse. The social media links that are integrated with Fuse include Blog, Facebook, Instagram, LinkedIn, Google Maps, Snapchat, Twitter, Yelp, and YouTube. Any other social media links cannot be added.

#### **System Integrations** 

The system integration section is where you can see what AMS is connected to the realm. If you have multiple lists, they will appear within this section. 

* What is a list?   
  * A unique set of accounts integrated from a management system.  
* Why would an agency have multiple lists?   
  * This is the only area you would be able to see an old list once it is disabled.   
  * Let's say a client has their own AMS360 instance and they sync it with Fuse. That's a list.  
  * Then let's say they acquire another agency, which already had its own separate AMS360 instance with their own separate data.   
    * And let's say the client decides that they're going to keep the acquired agency's data in its own separate AMS360 instance, but they want to sync it into Fuse.   
    * For that, they would need a second list, connected to their newly-acquired, separate AMS360 instance.   
    * It could certainly be on the same realm but they would have two separate AMS360 lists, each requiring its own separate integration, mapping, campaigns, and so-on.  
  * We also have some cases where multiple agencies have all of their data on a single, shared instance of a management system.   
    * This is common with agency clusters like Farmers Union, The Ahbe Group (TAG), Brown & Brown, and quite a few others. This is specific to Enterprise realms.   
    * In those cases, multiple agencies exist in a cluster in order to pool resources and save money on operating costs.   
    * So all of their data is in a single instance of a management system, but we need to sync separate chunks of that data into separate Fuse lists on separate realms that are operated by each separate agency within the cluster.   
    * In those cases, each agency that joins Fuse from the same cluster essentially uses all the same setup details   
      * (for example, if they're on AMS360, their integration setup utilizes the exact same configuration/connection) but then we filter which accounts are allowed into their list based on a key field...usually we filter them out based on either the Department, Agency, or Producer.  
  * In those cases, there is only 1 management system instance, but there are a lot of separate "lists" on separate realms within Fuse that are all connected to it.  
* Multiple lists  
  * If you see multiple lists, you can have one realm with multiple lists   
  * What happens if you see a company with different lists vs different realms   
    * How you know what list you are making the campaign in  
    * Use insuranceinc.com as an example   
    * Why do they have multiple lists? Did we mess up and not disable it   
    * If they have a valid reason for having multiple lists, you need to know what list to make it under   
    * List \= AMS System???   
  * How can you tell if a list is active vs not? (go to settings for that)

## Other Important Information

### Event Detector

#### Event Detector applies to all lists. 

* The "Event Detector" is a critical part of the system, and it does exactly what it sounds like: it detects events.  
* Events are also referred to sometimes as "Trigger Points".   
  * They indicate that an important event has occurred on a customer record, which may be a reason to add them to, or remove them from, a campaign.  
  * [Automating Your Campaigns with Trigger Points (Events)](https://help.agencyrevolution.com/en/articles/79897-automating-your-campaigns-with-trigger-points-events)

#### Event Logging

* When an event is detected, it is logged in Fuse under the Account's "Activities" tab as "Event Detected" along with the event's name.  
  * Fuse does not show an activity log for every event.   
    * Some events will not appear under the activities tab unless they are being used as a campaign trigger.  
    * Otherwise, the activities list would get way too cluttered with event logs that don't matter to the user.

#### Enabling & Disabling Event Detection

Sometimes, it's useful to temporarily disable event detection on a specific list, so that Fuse doesn't trigger a bunch of poorly-timed campaign subscriptions or removals.

Disabling/Enabling by Superusers  
Our support teams can disable or enable this feature when needed. The most common use-cases for manually disabling event detection are:

* Client purchased a new book of business and will be adding it to their integrated data all at once.  
  * In this case, disabling event detection prevents Fuse from noticing every active account that shows up while the new book of business is imported, and triggering "New Customer" events for all of them (which could result in sending poorly-timed Welcome Kits to hundreds or thousands of pre-existing customers)  
* A problem has prevented a client's list from integrating for a significant length of time  
  * In this case, if the sync problem is still ongoing, eventually some policies will start to expire and Fuse won't have new data to tell it if those policies have actually been renewed.   
  * So, disabling event detection can help to prevent the system from detecting "lost customer" events and sending poorly-timed/inaccurate "Customer Win-back" campaigns to customers that might not actually be lost.  
  * If the sync problem has gone on for a while but is fixed and the list is about to be re-synced to get all the data up-to-date, then disabling the event detector helps to avoid triggering untimely events that were missed while the sync was down.

Disabling/Enabling by Engineering Team

* Occasionally, our engineers will temporarily disable event detection while releasing an update that could otherwise result in the detection of unexpected or untimely events.   
* For example, if we're releasing an update to the way we map the policy inception date for Epic lists, the one-time mass-change of data could trigger inaccurate lost policy events, so event detection will be disabled, the update will be released, and then event detection will be re-enabled.   
* This typically happens overnight and has no impact on normal, day-to-day events.

Automatic Disabling/Enabling  
Fuse automatically does the following:

*  All new lists start with event detection disabled  
* Fuse will automatically enable event detection after the first time a list syncs  
* This should probably go into an internal help article somewhere, but I don't know if we have any kind of centralized place for that.

### Sequences

#### What is a sequence?

A sequence tells the campaign when it should do something.

* We can create a Steps, Account Date, or Specific Date sequence.   
* This will be the popup you will see when creating a campaign sequence. Once you click on “View/edit” from a custom campaign, you will see the sequence page where the messages are contained.   
* All aspects of the sequence can be edited. When selecting "Your Audience," you can choose the segment (group of accounts targeted) and the frequency of how often accounts are added to the sequence.  
* There are three different options for frequency (At launch, Ongoing, and In the Future).

### Why Use These Campaigns?

#### Welcome Kit for New Clients

Historically, this campaign has one of the highest open rates of any automated campaigns in Fuse. Additionally, it is an excellent way to easily make an outstanding first impression with new customers by communicating all about the agency. This campaign allows the client to:

* Introducing the agency’s team.  
* Pass along the carrier and claim information.   
* Share their website and social media information.   
* Inform clients on agency-specific items such as referral programs or agency applications.

#### Account Review for Current Clients

If an agency could only launch one campaign, this would win the prize. The Account Review campaign is an easy way to make the agency’s clients feel attended to without adding extra strain and resources on the agency. This campaign allows the agency to check in with clients once or twice a year to ask about the client’s life updates (to potentially earn more business).  

The Fuse team has found that customers give us more positive feedback from this campaign than any others.

#### Post Renewal Thank You

This campaign allows the agency to kill two birds with one stone. It works by showing appreciation to clients by thanking them for their continued business. In turn, the campaign will ask for a Google Review if they have had a good experience. 

#### Customer Appreciation Broadcast

This is the only broadcast that our team will implement by default because it is an easy way to get the agency started with Fuse. It really highlights the differences between a broadcast and a campaign. The email can give the agency’s clients the heads up to expect more emails from the agency in the near future.

#### Net Promoter Score

The NPS campaign is one of the easiest ways to feel the pulse of the agency’s clients.  The NPS campaign allows clients to give annual internal feedback on how the agency is performing.

* The information shared within the NPS is not public. Therefore, the information it gathers can help in resolving client issues before they become public. Additionally, the agency might be able to catch issues they didn’t know existed.    
* From our experience, the majority of the responses are very positive. If asked, the feedback can be used as testimonials on the client’s website.  
* A follow-up campaign can automatically be used to request Google reviews from positive responses.

### Domain Validation

Domain validation allows emails to appear to come straight from the agent’s emails. It typically takes on their domain name (hence the name, domain validation). 

One important thing to note is that Fuse will work without doing this step. However, the likelihood of emails going into a spam folder are higher.  

For this process, 4 options exist:

* Did not verify their domain.  
  * If the domain is unvalidated, emails will still send from Fuse. It display their email address as the sender and “via insuranceservices.email” after.  
* Website domain corresponding to email (most common).  
  * This is the most common option that lets the Fuse emails come from their domain.  
  * This can be verified either by their team or through the integration team with delegate access.   
    * If for some reason we cannot validate the domain, this is where we have to explore the following options:   
      * Set up a subdomain. (1 day)  
      * Revoke mailgun access to a prior company (2-7 days)  
* Non-Unique domain.  
  * This means that their emails are gmail.com, yahoo.com and they do not own the domain.	  
    * These emails are not recommended to use with any email integration software.   
* Multiple domains.  
  * There are a couple of different reasons why employee emails could use different domains.  
    * They rebranded and have multiple domains with active email addresses.   
      * Example: fmgsuite.com, agencyrevolution.com and forge3.com.  
    * They have a mix of gmail/outlook email addresses and their domain email addresses.

If we have any specific questions on this, refer to the [Fuse DNS Set Up Process](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1UbQz40MZYsq2h11O7HL5b10bIb15FNgdWTJmq7yCxXU/edit).

#### Creating a Custom Campaign

When choosing to create a custom campaign, start from the Template Library for a more guided approach or create one from scratch. This section will give you an overview of how a custom campaign functions.

There are basic parts of Fuse when it comes to sending messages. 

1\. The **Campaign**: Essentially what houses your sequences. 

The **Sequence**: The first option you have for a sequence starts on the campaign page when creating a new sequence. We can create a Steps, Account Date, or Specific Date sequence. This will be the popup you will see when creating a campaign sequence. Once you click on “View/edit” from a custom campaign, you will see the sequence page where the messages are contained. 

All aspects of the sequence can be edited. When selecting "Your Audience," you can choose the segment (group of accounts targeted) and the frequency of how often accounts are added to the sequence. There are three different options for frequency (At launch, Ongoing, and In the Future).

2\. The **Segment**: One of the most powerful features in Fuse is segmentation. Segments allow you to target your messages to exactly the right people. To make things easy \- we have two ways of creating segment rules. 

**Mad Libs** allows you to fill in the blanks on useful rules that should cover 80% of what you need.

**Advanced** allows you to create rules that cover any data field we receive from your AMS. The possibilities are endless.

# Best Practices

## Accounts Scenarios

### Why Should I Tag an Account in Fuse?

Tagging is a useful way to add custom data to records to further personalize marketing. It allows you to search Fuse for certain tags, a way to categorize, and segment your accounts based on various criteria. 

* Improved Organization: Tags help in organizing your accounts into different categories, which can be useful in managing and tracking them.  
* Targeted Communication: Tags allow you to create targeted communication and marketing campaigns. For instance, you can send a specific communication to all accounts tagged as 'VIP Customer'.  
* Automation: You can use tags to automate certain actions or sequences in Fuse. For example, when customers are tagged with a specific criterion, they can automatically be added to a specific sequence.  
* Easy Identification: Tags make it easier to identify and find particular accounts. For instance, you can quickly find all accounts tagged as 'New Customer'.  
* Segmentation: Tags can be used to create segments, which are subsets of your contacts that share certain characteristics. This allows for even more personalized and targeted communication.

#### How to Utilize Tagging

For example, you can do the following in Fuse to utilize tagging: 

* Tag an individual account.  
  * To tag an individual account, navigate to the Accounts page, and click "Add Tag."  
* Search for an account using a tag.  
  * In the accounts screen, simply click on "View Tags" and you will see a list of your tags.  
* Tag a Group of Accounts by Segment.  
  * If you can create a segment to identify who should have a tag, you can tag everyone at once.  
* Combine Tags With Other Segmentation Criteria  
  * You can do this by creating a new segment and adding a rule. Meaning “look in all accounts, but only show me accounts with ‘this’ tag”  
* Tag Accounts Who Complete a Form  
  * If you need clients to fill out a form and then be tagged that they filled it out, this can be done by adding a “tagging step” within the campaign. 

See [this Help Center guide](https://help.agencyrevolution.com/en/articles/1012492-tagging-accounts-in-fuse) to walk you through it. 

## Campaign Scenarios

### Recap: The 3 main types of campaigns:

* Steps Campaigns  
  * Steps campaigns are action-based sequences.   
  * They are triggered when a contact takes a specific action or meets certain criteria.   
    * For example, if a contact fills out a form on your website or clicks a link in an email, a Steps campaign could be triggered to send a follow-up email or assign a task for a sales representative to make a call.  
* Account Date Campaigns  
  * Account Date campaigns are triggered based on a specific date related to the contact's account.   
  * This could be the date the account was created, a policy renewal date, or a contact's birthday.   
    * For example, an Account Date campaign could send a policy renewal reminder email one month before the renewal date.  
* Specific Date Campaigns  
  * Specific Date campaigns are triggered on a set calendar date, regardless of any specific action or account-related date.  
  * These are typically used for one-off events or annual occurrences like holidays.  
    * For example, a Specific Date campaign could be used to send a promotional email on Black Friday.

### How to Review a Campaign

* Is the frequency correct?  
* Is the timing correct? (when emails will be sent to clients)  
* Do the merge fields make sense/have fallbacks?  
* Does the segment look correct (Do the subscribers make sense?)

### How Do You Avoid Message Overlap? 

Carefully consider how you time your sequence steps in any campaign related to Account Dates and/or Trigger Events. 

* If you want steps to run in relation to any date that comes from an account (like Customer Since date, Policy Effective Date, Policy Expiration Date, etc.) or any account-related event (like New Customer, Renewed Policy, Expired Policy, etc.) you should consider whether the timing of messages in any such campaigns will lead to frequent overlap of message timing, or overload of too many messages in a short time frame.  
* Our content team takes this into consideration when publishing campaigns to our library.   
* As much as possible, they are pre-configured to avoid too much overlap or overload.   
* However, it is ultimately up to the user to balance their messaging, make those decisions, and make adjustments if they ever notice somewhere that they can improve it.

### What is the Campaign Life Cycle?

Understanding the campaign life-cycle so you can edit, collaborate, and publish your campaign.

* #### Step 1: New

  * A new campaign can be created by scratch or imported from the Campaign Library. No one will receive your communications until it's launch.

* #### Step 2: Launched

  * Once a campaign is launched the last version you were worked on is available to the universe.

* #### Step 3: Editing

  * Found a typo or need to make a change? Just edit the campaign. Don't worry, no one will see your changes while you are drafting and modifying the campaign.

* #### ​Step 4: Relaunch

  * Happy with your changes? Relaunch the campaign to publish to the universe.  
* *\*\*\* **Note:** You can repeat steps 3 and 4 as often as you like.*

### What is the difference between Launch, Relaunch, Apply Edits, and Publish? 

#### Launch, Relaunch, Apply Edits

There are actually 3 different things that the launch button might say. They all do the same thing but the words are different depending on the current state of the campaign and any changes that might have been made to it. It may say...

* LAUNCH \- If the campaign has never been launched before  
* RELAUNCH \- If the campaign has been launched before, and there are currently NO pending edits to apply.  
* APPLY EDITS \- If the campaign has been launched before, and there ARE currently pending edits to apply.

After clicking that button (regardless of which thing it says), Fuse will show you the launch summary screen so you know what you're about to launch/relaunch, and as long as there's nothing wrong with the campaign, you'll have the "GO LIVE" button on that screen to proceed with the launch.

#### Publish

The PUBLISH buttons are ONLY used for publishing something to the Fuse content library.

* Standard client users don't see the PUBLISH buttons.  
* If you're a superuser you can see these buttons but as a general rule...don't use them\!  
* The only people who should really be using the PUBLISH buttons are:  
  * Our content team  
  * Enterprise Admin users who have a special configuration that lets them publish content only to their own member realms.  
  * Enterprise Support, when helping an Enterprise Admin to publish content to member realms

### What is the common behavior of activating and deactivating Quick Start campaigns.

Here is an example:

* I’ve launched the ‘Quick Start Campaign: New Customer Welcome Campaign.’   
* After running it for a few months I decided to deactivate it.   
* I am now ready to relaunch, what will happen?   
* Will a customer who was supposed to receive message \#3 months ago, get that same message tomorrow?

That depends on how long the campaign was paused and what type of campaign:

* Event-Triggered Campaigns that use Steps and have been paused for more than 2 weeks will NOT resume messages for existing subscribers.  
* Event-Triggered Campaigns that use Dates will resume for all subscribers.  
* All Ongoing Campaigns that use Dates or Steps will resume for all subscribers.

### What happens when relaunching a campaign?

After you launch a campaign, there are times you may want to make a change. Any time you make a change to the emails or steps in a sequence you should relaunch your campaign to apply the edits. 

*\*\*\* **Note:** Changes are NOT applied to your campaign until this is done.*

By selecting ‘Apply Edits’ you are able to review the changes before they are applied. On the bottom right you will need to select ‘Go Live’

### How to Clone Campaigns.

Cloning campaigns is a best practice to follow, generally. It allows you to: 

* Duplicate the same content for a new segment of customers.  
* Re-run an old/completed campaign.  
* Restart a campaign from scratch if you made a mistake with the first attempt.

For example, you could clone your "Home no Auto" cross-sell campaign and easily change the clone into an "Auto no Home" cross-sell.

#### Cloning Steps Example

Turn a "Home no Auto" cross-sell campaign into an "Auto no Home”

* From the campaign overview, click the 3-dot menu & choose "Clone Campaign"  
* Fuse immediately takes you to the newly cloned version (you'll notice all Sequence titles say "COPIED"). Now edit your sequence names & message content to fit the needs of your new version (e.g. \- change "Home no Auto" to "Auto no Home", etc.)  
*  Change the target segment within each sequence if your new version is meant for a different group of people.  
* Edit the message content to fit your new version.  
* Launch your new campaign\!

### Where Does the "Customer Since" Date Come From?

"Customer Since" date is the default date field for our Account Review Campaign.

#### Where can I find this?

The "Customer Since" date appears on each Account in two places: 

* Once as a specific date.  
* Once as a generalized timeframe.

#### Where does the "Customer Since" date come from?

There are two possibilities, depending on your management system:

1. If your Agency Management System has a "Customer Since" field, Fuse will use that directly.  
2. If there is no "Customer Since" Date in your management system, Fuse will extrapolate the date based on the earliest policy effective date found on the customer's account, or in some cases based on the "First Written" date on the oldest policy.

#### How is the "Customer Since" date used?

The "Customer Since" date is the default date field used in the stock ‘Account Review’ Campaign.  This is different from a Renewal Campaign which is tied to a specific policy or policies.

When using this field for an account review, it will only occur once per year, on the "anniversary" of the date when the account first became a customer.

[Source](https://help.agencyrevolution.com/en/articles/423037-where-does-the-customer-since-date-come-from)

#### Customer Since Date v. Policy Expiration Date

Customer Since Date

* We use Customer Since Date because it’s an account level date vs. a policy level date. The downside is that this date becomes inaccurate if a client moves AMS’, since at that point all of their customers will have the same customer since date. We should ask if the client ever changed AMS’.  
* This is the default date for our Account Review Campaign.  
* When using this field for that campaign, it will only occur once per year, on the “anniversary” of the date when the account first became a customer.

Policy Expiration Date

* We can target only once per account and will target the highest premium policy on the account and only that one.   
* The downside is if a client has 6 month policies, this could become an issue because this will not trigger.   
* We should ask if a client has 6-month policies and would your 6-month policy be the highest premium.

#### Determining the Use of ‘Customer Since Date’ or ‘Policy Effective/Expiration’ Date

* Have you ever changed AMS’?   
* Do you have 6-month policies?  
* If so, do they have a higher premium?

## Sequence Scenarios 

### Better understanding of date sequences.

Choosing the right kind of sequence is critical\! After a sequence has been launched, it is not possible to change it from a step sequence to a date sequence or from one type of date sequence to another.

*\*\*\* **Note:** You can always clone a sequence, make changes, and then launch a new version. However, once launched, these aspects of a sequence are locked.*

#### Remind me \- what’s a sequence?

A sequence tells the campaign when it should do something. 

There are three different options for frequency (At launch, Ongoing, and In the Future).

#### Types of date sequences.

* Step Sequence  
* Account Date Sequence  
* Specific Date Sequence

#### Specific Date \- Run Once 

This option runs only once in relation to the specific month, day, and year you choose. This mode also provides an option to specify the year in which it must run, or to select "any year."  

* Selecting "any year," tells Fuse that any step for which the relevant timing has already passed during the current calendar year should be scheduled for the next calendar year instead. 

#### Specific Date \- Run Annually

This option runs every year in relation to the specific month and day you choose.

#### Account Date \- Run Exactly Once

Step timing is unique for each subscriber and it is relative to the account-based date field you select. The "Run Exactly Once" option schedules itself to run just once in relation to the current value in your selected account date field.  If the value in the account's relevant date field is altered before the sequence has run for them, the steps will be rescheduled to correlate with the changed date. However, after the sequence has run once for any given account, it will not run for that account again.  

#### Account Date \- Run Annually and Reschedule if Date Changes

Step timing is unique for each subscriber and is relative to the account-based date field you select. This option schedules its steps to run at the next available opportunity in relation to the month and day in the account date field you've selected. If the last step in the sequence is reached, it will automatically reschedule all steps to run again in relation to the same date the following year. Also, if the value in the account's relevant date field is altered, the sequence will reschedule its steps to correlate with that changed date.

### Icons for Different Types of Sequences

![][image12]

* **Yellow** \= steps sequence based on action like a form submitted to move through the next steps   
* **Blue** \= steps sequence based on date either an account date or a specific date   
* **Green** \=  Form

### How to Clone Sequences

#### Why Clone a Sequence?

This allows you to run multiple versions of a sequence with minor differences:   
​(e.g. \- A "Home no Auto" campaign with branch-specific sequences like "Home no Auto \- North Branch" and "Home no Auto \- South Branch", with slightly different, branch-specific content)

Segment your target list into smaller chunks:   
​(e.g. \- One sequence for last names A-M which runs one month, and another for last names N-Z which runs the next month).

*\*\*\* **Notes**:*

* *You can also clone specific sequences within a campaign.*  
* *Sequences retain their sequence type when being cloned. For example, you can NOT change a date sequence to a step sequence by cloning. However, before launching the clone you CAN change other factors like the event triggers, anchor dates, and segments targeted.*

#### Sequence Cloning Steps: 

1. From within the sequence, click "Options", then "Clone Sequence".  
2. Give the clone a new name and click "Clone"  
3. Change the target segment as needed.  
4. Edit the message content to fit your new version.  
5. When ready, click "Apply Edits" from the campaign summary screen to launch.  
6. ​Note: Your new sequence (the clone you just created) will not be live until you click "Apply Edits."

### General Pausing Notes

* You have the ability to pause sequences but you have to launch the entire campaign. You cannot pause the campaign as a whole.   
  * Pause literally stops emails from going out.   
  * You don’t need to pause the campaign to make changes.   
  * Good idea to pause when there are big errors or we need to research things.   
  * Won’t retroactively remove things from the Outbox so if you pause things may already be in Outbox so review that.   
* As a best practice, it is a good idea to rename the sequence “PAUSE” when pausing so it is obvious to the client.   
* If you make a change when paused, you need to Apply Edits before unpausing the sequence.   
* You need to restart to get the campaign to unpause. You don’t need to relaunch the campaign. Relaunch is a safeguard to make sure things are working as they need to.   
* The audience is still active when things are paused. 

### How Pausing a Sequence Affects the Timing

#### Step Sequences

Pausing a step sequence with existing subscribers will pause all actions.

* When the sequence is unpaused, the actions will resume.   
* Therefore, if you pause a sequence for a day, you'll have an extra day of delay in your sequence. If you pause a sequence for two months then everything will be delayed for two months.


*\*\*\* **Note:** If your sequence is paused for a long time, you may consider removing all subscribers before unpausing it.*

####  Date Sequences

Pausing a date sequence, whether it's a specific date or an account date, will skip any step that should have happened on the date the sequence is paused. When resumed, any scheduled steps will then happen.

## Segment Scenarios 

### What is a segment vs an audience? 

Segment is anyone and everyone who fits the segment criteria. It’s sort of the starting point. The Audience is who is actually getting the email after the system audits the segment and determines the unsubscribes, clients without email, triggers, etc.

### Madlib Segmenting 

#### What Should We Know About This?

As a best practice, you should start with the madlib version of segmenting. It allows you to be as accurate as possible. If you need to add advanced segmenting, do it after starting with the madlibs version. 

#### How to Use Them

The power of advanced segments can be overwhelming. Save yourself time and start by exploring the Madlib segments.

Accounts \> Add a Segment \> Determine who your target audience is.   
![][image13]  
You can click on one of the Madlibs to plug in the data. In the example below, we have selected "Account by Status or Type." The blue words are fields where you select the information. Click on each field to change the options:

Segments are dynamically adjusting so they will always stay up-to-date as long as the data from your management software is being updated. So anytime a client status or type changes, they will automatically be removed from the segment since they no longer match the rules you have created.

### Advanced Segmenting 

#### Lucas's 4 Rules for Creating Accurate Segments

* Less Is More  
* Define Your Segment in Plain English  
* Audit Your Results  
* Read Your Segment Back in Plain English

#### Understanding the Data Structure

One of the keys to creating good segments is understanding the data structure we use for Fuse. The data we have is divided into four groups: Account, Policy, Claim, and your AMS data.

* Account  
  * Data that relates to the customer in your system. Here we may also include some "summary" properties of the entire account.  
* Policy  
  * Property specific policies that are useful for fine-tuning.  
* Claim  
  * Claim specific properties.  
* Your System  
  * All the data we get from your AMS, useful for custom properties or unique data that only your AMS has.

## Form Scenarios

### Form Basics

* Users encounter the form as an email. But the form lives in the Campaign “folder” so you have everything in one place.   
* Form is hidden in the preview of campaigns in the library.   
* Follow up can be confirmation text or you can redirect to website   
* Responses will have a list of the responses from the form and see the details.   
  * Responses will show on the account but there is a “Follow up” sequence that alerts the agency.   
  * Often adds a tag once a form is submitted so you can sort for those who submitted.   
  * Confirmation/Follow Up sends to agent and the client.   
* The form is added to emails as a button. 

### What Happens to Contacts When They Fill Out My Fuse Forms?

#### When Non-Customers Fill Out Fuse Forms

* When someone fills out a Fuse form, that contact is added to your Agency Revolution Fuse database. They're considered to be a "disconnected" contact because they did not enter Fuse by way of integration.  
* There is a visual indication next to a customer record in Fuse, indicating they're a "disconnected contact." You will see a yellow triangle with an exclamation next to their name. When you mouse over that icon, the words "disconnected" will display, indicating this contact entered your Fuse account by way of a Fuse form.  
* This new contact will not push back into your management system. If you later enter the contact as a customer in your database, so long as you use the same email address that was supplied when the contact filled out the form when adding the customer to your management system, it will then merge the disconnected contact data with your newly added data from your management system when we receive that data by way of integration.

#### When Customers Fill Out Fuse Forms

* If your current customer fills out the form with the same email address we have in Fuse, the records will merge on that email address, and the additional data supplied in the form will be connected to that existing record.   
* If the current customer fills out a Fuse form with a different email address than the one we have for them in Fuse, a new "disconnected" record will be generated.   
* If multiple contacts in Fuse use the same email address that is supplied when your current customer fills out a Fuse form, Fuse will merge the form data into the first record that Fuse encounters sharing that email address. It is important to be mindful of this. 

### How Do I Set Up a Website Form and Follow-Up Campaign?

#### Setting up the Form

* First, navigate to your Content Library by clicking on "Content Library" in the left navigation bar.  
* In the Content Library, scroll down until you locate the Forms and Form Follow-Up items.  
* Customize the Website Form  
  * Click "Customize" on the campaign you would like to set up.  
  * Then select "View/Edit" on the form.  
  * Once you're done editing your form, you can hit "Preview" to see how the form is going to be displayed. Once you're done viewing your form you can hit the "Done" button. 

#### From the form builder is where you can:

* **Add additional fields** to your form. You can see they are categorized by the most popular fields as well as added generic fields that you can customize.   
  * It is always good to remember that less is more when adding fields to a form. Having more than five fields in any form can drop your conversion rate drastically. 


* **Remove fields** by clicking on the field you want to remove, selecting the trash can, and then selecting delete.  
* **Edit existing fields** by clicking on the field and changing the description and whether that field is required.  
* **Edit the submission button text, confirmation text** (this is what is displayed on the web page after the form is submitted), or you can redirect a thank you landing page if you have one created. You can also **determine lead ownership of the form** which means that person by default will receive the follow-up email after submission. 

#### Setting up a Website Form Follow-Up Campaign

* Next, select the "Follow-Up" tab. This is where you can review and edit the "Thank You" email that's sent to the customer and the internal follow-up email.   
* Under the form follow-up sequence, select "View".  
* Select the pencil icon next to the title of the first email to start editing.  
* Once you've finished editing the email, select the "Save & Preview" button in the upper left corner to preview your email.  
* You can then select "Done" to save your changes.  
* Now, let's edit the second email in the sequence. This is the internal email sent after the customer has submitted their form responses. You'll want to add the correct merge fields that will pull the correct data from the form after it has been submitted.

#### Launching the Website Form

* Once finished editing the internal email, you can embed the form onto our clients existing website, if we have access (Attract/Forge). However, before you can embed the form, launch it by clicking "Launch" on the bottom right corner.  
* Review changes, and click "Go Live" to launch the form\! 

## Mapping Scenarios

Mapping dictates what employees show as Account Reps or Producers on accounts in Fuse. 

Mapping is not available for every realm. 

Any employees that come through the Management system, need to be mapped to a user in Fuse. If this user's customer accounts should not show in Fuse, the employee will need to be updated in the AMS or excluded from the list either in the AMS or through Fuse. This is AMS specific.

If employees show up on accounts as the producer or account rep type fields, it will show up in Fuse.

We cannot map by anything else other than the Rep or producer that is currently assigned to an account. For example, we cannot map accounts alphabetically to specific employees.

### What is Considered a Mapping Issue? 

An indicator that something is a mapping issue is when the email a campaign has sent out is incorrect. 

For example, if you see data on the Foreign data but this field is not showing on the Account data tab on a specific account, this is a mapping issue. A specific example would be a policy expiration date not showing correctly on the account but the data showing on the foreign (unmapped data). 

There can be two mapping issues that cause issues in Fuse: 

* Employees or policy mapping needs to be corrected. This relates to the above section.   
* The account has the correct information synced but it doesn't show in the correct area (Fuse mapped data). In this case, we can remap individual accounts in Fuse and the full list.

#### Accurate Employee Mapping

To ensure accurate employee mapping, it is important to follow these steps. 

* If there is a need to remove users or employees, please note that their removal from our system alone is not sufficient.   
* They must also be removed from the client's AMS to be completely removed from the accounts.   
* It is crucial to understand that we cannot directly adjust mapping in Fuse.   
* This information should be effectively communicated to the client, emphasizing the importance of their involvement in removing the individual from their AMS for a complete removal from the accounts.

## Overall Best Practices

### How can I tell if a client is engaged with Fuse? 

We can look at our engagement score within Fuse, but, here are some other practical places to look: 

* Is their list syncing regularly?  
* Is their engagement score 1 or above? (Means an average of 1 email/month/active account)  
* Is their email open rate 20% or above? (Industry avg is 2-25%)  
* Do they have at least 80% of active accounts with emails?  
* How many campaigns do they have running and are they in line with the segmentation of their book?

### What can we do to help a client with bad data/dirty data?

When a client has dirty data, our team needs to communicate that the goal is to get started to get better. 

1. Can use segmenting to target those accounts that need to be updated.  
2. Can eliminate the name field or just use a different field.  
3. Unable to Email Campaign \- 100 days before the policy expiration date \- email goes to whoever they set.  
4. Outbox can also be used to make last minute changes…you can make the change in the Outbox, but then you also have to make the change in the AMS as well.

All of this has to happen by the client within their AMS system. Then the correct data gets synced with Fuse. 

### When it comes to alerts, how does a client know these alerts exist? 

* All alerts appear under the bell icon when logged into Fuse  
* If an integration is not working, this generates an out-of-sync alert. Clients are also notified when their list is out-of-sync via:  
  * Daily SMS message (every morning at 10am) to the phone of any user who, under their user settings in Fuse, has (A) Toggled on "I am responsible for managing syncing data to Fuse", and (B) Entered their cellphone number  
  * Weekly "Integration Recap" email (this email includes other info, but includes the out-of-sync alert if applicable)  
* For all other alerts (pending file review step, unmapped employees or policy codes, unverified email domain, something wrong or incomplete with a campaign, etc.) a user needs to log into Fuse to see them.

### Regarding lists, how can you tell if a list is actively being used?

The key factors are probably:

* Is the integration working/current? If it hasn't synced in 3 months, for example, something is wrong.   
  * However, the question then is whether it's intentional or not (is it broken and they didn't notice? did they stop it on purpose because they got a new management system and now are syncing that one? have they given up on Fuse? etc.)  
* Are there live campaigns or recent broadcasts?  
* Check their dashboard. How are their "email sends" and engagement score looking?

### Reporting incorrect events.

If a client experienced an incorrect event, we need to figure out what happened.

#### Common Scenarios

* Data is not mapped correctly.   
  * In this case, there is nothing we can do to fix the event engine to solve the scenario. Instead, we'll assist you in improving your data mapping to avoid this case in the future.  
* Data is something unusual that we've never seen before.   
  * Agency Management Systems are flexible and allow many possible ways to structure the data. We can't always handle every scenario, but we will do our best to accommodate you.

### Email Best Practices

#### Email Spam and Deliverability

 There are 6 category reports to analyze each message to help you with deliverability.

* To analyze your email for spam and deliverability, in the Email Builder, select "Preview & Test" in the top menu bar.  
* In this Preview Pane, select "Spam Analysis.”  
* The report will run through 6 different categories and find potential issues that can be addressed to increase your email deliverability.  
* You will be given a score from 1 to 10, where 10 is a perfect score.   
  * A perfect score or a bad score doesn't mean your email will or won't be delivered. It's just a generalization to help you meet best practices.

#### Images in Emails

We don't recommend sending emails with just images and I follow the 60/40 rule. 60% text to 40% image ratio. It can negatively impact the effectiveness of your email marketing campaign.

* Using images is a great way to make an email engaging. However, we do not recommend sending emails with just images and suggest following the 60/40 rule \- 60% text to 40% image ratio.

### Account Basics

#### Updating a User Password

* To change your password or a user's password, first, navigate to the gear icon located in the top right corner of your dashboard and click "All Settings."  
* In the settings menu located on the left side of your screen, click "Users."  
* Click on the name of the user that you would like to change the password for, and then select "Change Password."  
* Here, you will be prompted to enter the new password. Click "Save," and now your password has been changed\!

#### Restrict Login Access

A user may want to send emails on behalf of an employee but not allow them to log into Fuse? When adding the user, ensure that the "Allow this user to login" is toggled off.

If the user has already been added, you can disable them, and they won't be able to log in. 

#### Disable or Delete a User

To disable or delete a user:

1. Select the user from the user list.  
2. Click "Option,” and select either.  
   1. Disable User: Remove login access  
   2. Delete User: Remove the user completely from your account.  
3. Click “Save” to apply your changes. 

#### Producer Updates

Before removing a producer account we must verify the following:

* The user is looking to remove all accounts associated with a producer or if they would like to remap all the accounts to go to another producer.   
* Does the Producer have code associated with them?   
  * The producer might have code associated with them, however if we do not see this in our system, it might be from their AMS. There might be a list of producers associated with the code.

#### Business Texting \- Best Practices

* Enable notifications on their computer.  
* \*\*\***Important**: Do not blast messages to large lists\!
